<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900814-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>900814-0028.</DOCID><HL>   Equitec Posts Loss   In Quarter, Discloses   Default on All Debt</HL><DATE>08/14/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12</SO><CO>   EFG</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)</IN><LP>   OAKLAND, Calif. -- Equitec Financial Group Inc., posting anet loss for the second quarter of $3.4 million, or 68 centsa share, disclosed it now is in default on all of its debtobligations outstanding.   For the year-ago period, the financial services companyhad a loss of $3.3 million, or 68 cents a share. That figureincludes a loss of $2 million from discontinued operations.</LP><TEXT>   Revenue for the recent period declined 30%, to $8.3million from $11.8 million.   For the six months ended June 30, Equitec posted a netloss of $8.8 million, or $1.78 a share, which includes lossesfrom continuing operations of $7.7 million and fromdiscontinued operations of $1.1 million.   For the year-earlier period, Equitec had a net loss of$4.6 million, or 93 cents a share, which included losses fromcontinuing operations of $2.6 million, and from discontinuedoperations of $2 million.   Revenue for the recent six months declined 25%, to $16.8million from $22.3 million.   During the quarter just ended, Equitec said it failed tomake the interest payment on its 12% senior subordinateddebentures, thus placing it in default on all its debtoutstanding.   Richard L. Saalfield, Equitec chairman and chief executiveofficer, said the company continues to work with its advisersto &quot;investigate alternative methods of restructuring its debtand other obligations.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>